{
  "When a red snapdragon (RR) is crossed with a white snapdragon (R'R'), the offspring are all pink. This pattern of inheritance is called:": "",
  "Polygenic inheritance": "",
  "Complete dominance": "",
  "Incomplete dominance": "",
  "Codominance": "",
  "Incomplete dominance occurs when the heterozygote shows a blended, intermediate phenotype between the two homozygotes. Pink flowers from a red × white cross are the classic example — neither allele is fully dominant, so the result is a blend.": "",
  "A person with type AB blood expresses both A antigens and B antigens on their red blood cells. This is an example of:": "",
  "Epistasis": "",
  "X-linked inheritance": "",
  "In codominance, both alleles are fully and simultaneously expressed in the heterozygote. A person with genotype IᴬIᴮ displays BOTH A and B antigens — they are not blended into an intermediate, but both are distinctly present.": "",
  "The ABO blood group system has three alleles in the population: Iᴬ, Iᴮ, and i. This is an example of:": "",
  "Multiple alleles": "",
  "Pleiotropy": "",
  "Multiple alleles means more than two alleles exist in the population for a single gene, even though each individual only carries two. The ABO system has three alleles (Iᴬ, Iᴮ, and i), producing four possible blood types: A, B, AB, and O.": "",
  "Traits such as human skin color and height are controlled by many genes, each contributing a small effect. This pattern is called:": "",
  "Polygenic inheritance involves multiple genes (sometimes hundreds) each contributing a small additive effect to a single trait. This produces a continuous range of phenotypes and a bell-shaped distribution, unlike the distinct categories seen in simple Mendelian traits.": "",
  "Sickle cell disease is caused by one gene mutation but affects many organs including the blood, spleen, kidneys, and brain. This is an example of:": "",
  "Pleiotropy is when a single gene influences multiple, seemingly unrelated traits. The sickle cell gene (HbS) alters hemoglobin shape, which causes a cascade of effects throughout the body — anemia, organ damage, pain crises, and more — all from one mutation.": "",
  "In Labrador retrievers, the E gene controls pigment deposition. Dogs with the ee genotype are yellow regardless of their genotype at the B gene. This interaction between two genes is called:": "",
  "Epistasis occurs when one gene masks or modifies the expression of another gene at a different locus. In Labs, the E gene is epistatic to the B gene — the ee genotype prevents any pigment from being deposited in the fur, making the dog yellow no matter what B alleles it carries.": "",
  "Red-green color blindness and hemophilia are more common in males because the genes are located on the:": "",
  "X chromosome": "",
  "Y chromosome": "",
  "Mitochondrial DNA": "",
  "Autosome (chromosome 9)": "",
  "Color blindness and hemophilia are X-linked recessive traits. Males (XY) only have one X chromosome, so a single recessive allele on that X is expressed. Females (XX) need two copies of the recessive allele to show the trait, making it far less common in females.": "",
  "In incomplete dominance, the phenotypic ratio in the F2 generation (from crossing two heterozygotes) is:": "",
  "1:1": "",
  "3:1": "",
  "1:2:1": "",
  "9:3:3:1": "",
  "In incomplete dominance, the heterozygote has a distinct intermediate phenotype, so all three genotypes (homozygous dominant, heterozygous, homozygous recessive) look different. This gives a 1:2:1 phenotypic ratio instead of the classic 3:1 ratio seen in complete dominance.": "",
  "Which blood type is considered the universal donor for red blood cell transfusions?": "",
  "Type B": "",
  "Type O": "",
  "Type A": "",
  "Type AB": "",
  "Type O blood (genotype ii) has neither A nor B antigens on its red blood cells, so it does not trigger an immune reaction in recipients with any blood type. Type AB is the universal recipient because individuals with AB blood have both antigens and produce no anti-A or anti-B antibodies.": "",
  "Why are males more likely than females to express X-linked recessive traits?": "",
  "Males have only one X chromosome, so one recessive allele is enough to cause the trait": "",
  "X-linked genes are only active in male cells": "",
  "Testosterone activates recessive alleles in males": "",
  "Males have two X chromosomes, doubling their chance of inheriting the allele": "",
  "Males are hemizygous for X-linked genes — they have only one X (from their mother) and one Y. Because there is no second X to carry a dominant allele that could mask the recessive one, any recessive allele on the X is expressed. Females need two copies of the recessive allele (one on each X) to show the trait.": "",
  "Which of the following best defines incomplete dominance?": "",
  "A pattern where the heterozygote shows a blended, intermediate phenotype between the two homozygotes": "",
  "A pattern where a gene on the X chromosome is only expressed in males": "",
  "A pattern where both alleles are fully and simultaneously expressed in the heterozygote": "",
  "A pattern where one allele completely masks the other in the heterozygote": "",
  "Incomplete dominance produces a heterozygote phenotype that is intermediate between the two homozygotes. The key word is 'blended' — for example, red × white producing pink. Neither allele fully dominates, so the result appears to be a mixture of both parental traits.": "",
  "Which of the following best defines codominance?": "",
  "A pattern where many genes each contribute to one trait": "",
  "A pattern where both alleles are fully and distinctly expressed at the same time in the heterozygote": "",
  "A pattern where the heterozygote shows a blended intermediate phenotype": "",
  "A pattern where one gene masks the expression of another gene at a different locus": "",
  "In codominance, both alleles contribute equally and distinctly to the phenotype — they do not blend. Examples include AB blood type (both A and B antigens present) and roan cattle (separate red and white hairs side by side). The critical distinction from incomplete dominance is that both traits appear fully, not as a mix.": "",
  "Which of the following best defines polygenic inheritance?": "",
  "A pattern where multiple genes each contribute small additive effects to a single trait, producing continuous variation": "",
  "A pattern where more than two alleles exist for one gene in a population": "",
  "A pattern where one gene masks the expression of another gene": "",
  "A pattern where one gene controls multiple unrelated traits": "",
  "Polygenic inheritance means MANY genes → ONE trait. Each gene adds a small effect, and together they produce a continuous range of phenotypes (like height or skin color) that follow a bell curve. This is the opposite of pleiotropy (ONE gene → MANY traits).": "",
  "Which of the following best defines epistasis?": "",
  "A pattern where traits are linked to sex chromosomes": "",
  "A pattern where heterozygotes show a blended phenotype": "",
  "A pattern where one gene masks or modifies the phenotypic expression of a different gene": "",
  "Epistasis is a gene-gene interaction where one gene (the epistatic gene) controls whether another gene (the hypostatic gene) is expressed. Labrador coat color is the classic example: the E gene determines whether pigment is deposited at all, overriding whatever the B gene codes for.": "",
  "Which of the following best defines pleiotropy?": "",
  "A pattern where a single gene influences multiple, seemingly unrelated phenotypic traits": "",
  "A pattern where more than two alleles exist for a gene in the population": "",
  "A pattern where many genes each contribute a small amount to one trait": "",
  "Pleiotropy means ONE gene → MANY traits. The sickle cell gene is a classic example: a single mutation in the beta-globin gene causes anemia, joint pain, organ damage, and increased malaria resistance — all from one gene. Pleiotropy is the conceptual opposite of polygenic inheritance.": "",
  "Which of the following best defines the term 'multiple alleles'?": "",
  "A gene that has more than two allele forms within the population, though each individual still carries only two": "",
  "A trait controlled by many different genes on different chromosomes": "",
  "A situation where the heterozygote shows a blended phenotype": "",
  "A mutation that creates a new gene not previously found in a species": "",
  "Multiple alleles means more than two versions of a gene exist in the population. The ABO blood type system is the best example: three alleles (Iᴬ, Iᴮ, i) exist, but any one person only has two of them. This is different from polygenic inheritance, where many genes (not many alleles of one gene) affect a trait.": "",
  "Which of the following best defines a sex-linked trait?": "",
  "A trait that only appears in one sex due to hormonal differences": "",
  "A trait that is always dominant in males and recessive in females": "",
  "A trait that requires genes from both the X and Y chromosomes": "",
  "A trait controlled by a gene located on a sex chromosome (usually the X chromosome)": "",
  "Sex-linked traits are determined by genes on sex chromosomes. Most sex-linked traits in humans are X-linked because the X chromosome is much larger and carries many more genes than the Y. Hemophilia and red-green color blindness are classic X-linked recessive examples.": "",
  "In genetics, what is a carrier?": "",
  "An individual who is homozygous dominant and always expresses the trait": "",
  "A chromosome that transports genes from one cell to another": "",
  "An individual who is homozygous recessive and shows the full disorder": "",
  "An individual who is heterozygous for a recessive allele and can pass it on without showing symptoms": "",
  "A carrier is heterozygous — they have one dominant and one recessive allele. The dominant allele masks the recessive one, so the carrier appears unaffected, but they can pass the recessive allele to offspring. This is especially important for X-linked traits, where carrier mothers can pass the allele to sons who will express it.": "",
  "Which of the following best defines X-linked inheritance?": "",
  "A pattern where alleles on the Y chromosome are always dominant": "",
  "A pattern where the gene responsible for a trait is located on the X chromosome, causing different expression rates in males and females": "",
  "A pattern where traits skip every other generation regardless of sex": "",
  "A pattern where genes on any chromosome are expressed differently based on the sex of the individual": "",
  "X-linked inheritance specifically refers to genes on the X chromosome. Because males (XY) have only one X, they are hemizygous — a single recessive allele is expressed. Females (XX) have two copies, so they need two recessive alleles to show the trait. This is why X-linked recessive disorders are far more common in males.": "",
  "What does the term 'autosomal' mean in genetics?": "",
  "Located on the X chromosome only": "",
  "A gene that is only expressed during embryonic development": "",
  "A gene that is automatically expressed regardless of dominance": "",
  "Located on one of the 22 non-sex chromosomes (autosomes) rather than on the X or Y chromosome": "",
  "Autosomes are the 22 pairs of non-sex chromosomes in humans (chromosomes 1–22). An autosomal trait is inherited equally by males and females because the gene is not on a sex chromosome. Sickle cell disease and cystic fibrosis are examples of autosomal recessive disorders.": "",
  "A mother has type A blood (Iᴬi) and a father has type B blood (Iᴮi). What are all the possible blood types of their children?": "",
  "Type A, Type B, Type AB, and Type O": "",
  "Only Type O": "",
  "Only Type A and Type B": "",
  "Only Type AB": "",
  "Using a Punnett square: Mother (IᴬI) × Father (Iᴮi) → IᴬIᴮ (type AB), Iᴬi (type A), Iᴮi (type B), ii (type O). All four blood types are possible, each with a 25% chance. This cross beautifully demonstrates multiple alleles and codominance (in the AB offspring) simultaneously.": "",
  "In snapdragons, flower color shows incomplete dominance: RR = red, RR' = pink, R'R' = white. If two pink snapdragons (RR') are crossed, what fraction of the offspring will be pink?": "",
  "1/4 (25%)": "",
  "3/4 (75%)": "",
  "All of them (100%)": "",
  "1/2 (50%)": "",
  "RR' × RR' → 1 RR (red) : 2 RR' (pink) : 1 R'R' (white). So 2 out of 4 (50%) are pink. This 1:2:1 phenotypic ratio is the hallmark of incomplete dominance. Note that the phenotypic and genotypic ratios are identical because every genotype produces a unique phenotype.": "",
  "A woman who is a carrier for color blindness (X^C X^c) has children with a man who has normal vision (X^C Y). What is the probability that a DAUGHTER will be color blind?": "",
  "100% — all daughters inherit at least one recessive allele from the carrier mother": "",
  "50% — half the daughters will inherit the recessive allele": "",
  "0% — daughters will be either carriers or have normal vision": "",
  "25% — one quarter of all children will be affected": "",
  "Daughters receive one X from each parent. Father always gives X^C (normal). Mother gives either X^C or X^c. So daughters are either X^C X^C (normal) or X^C X^c (carrier, but pheno­typically normal). No daughter can be X^c X^c because the father cannot contribute X^c. To have a color-blind daughter, the father would also need to be color blind (X^c Y).": "",
  "Two parents both have medium skin tone. Their children range from very light to very dark skin. This wide variation is best explained by:": "",
  "Simple Mendelian dominance — one allele masks all others": "",
  "Sex-linked inheritance — skin color genes are on the X chromosome": "",
  "Polygenic inheritance — many genes contribute, and offspring can receive different combinations of alleles": "",
  "Incomplete dominance — the trait blends in every generation": "",
  "Skin color is a polygenic trait controlled by at least 15 genes. Medium-toned parents who are heterozygous at many loci can produce children with many different allele combinations — from mostly 'light' alleles to mostly 'dark' alleles. This creates a wide range of phenotypes not possible with a single gene.": "",
  "Both parents have type AB blood (IᴬIᴮ). Which of the following blood types is IMPOSSIBLE in their children?": "",
  "IᴬIᴮ × IᴬIᴮ → IᴬIᴬ (type A), IᴬIᴮ (type AB), IᴮIᴬ (type AB), IᴮIᴮ (type B). Neither parent carries the i allele, so the ii genotype (type O) is impossible. Children can be type A (25%), AB (50%), or B (25%).": "",
  "A roan horse has a coat with distinct red hairs and distinct white hairs — NOT pink hairs. If two roan horses (C^R C^W) are crossed, what phenotypic ratio do you expect in the offspring?": "",
  "1 red : 2 roan : 1 white": "",
  "All roan": "",
  "3 roan : 1 white": "",
  "1 red : 1 roan": "",
  "Roan is a codominant trait: C^R C^R = all red, C^R C^W = roan (both red and white expressed), C^W C^W = all white. Crossing two heterozygotes (roan × roan) yields a 1:2:1 ratio — same as incomplete dominance but the mechanism differs. In codominance, both alleles are fully expressed side by side rather than blended.": "",
  "A carrier mother (X^H X^h) for hemophilia and an unaffected father (X^H Y) have children. What fraction of ALL their children (sons and daughters combined) are expected to have hemophilia?": "",
  "0%": "",
  "Possible offspring: X^H X^H (normal daughter), X^H X^h (carrier daughter), X^H Y (normal son), X^h Y (hemophiliac son). Only one out of four possible outcomes produces hemophilia (the affected son). So 25% of ALL children are expected to be hemophiliac. Note: 50% of SONS will be affected, but across all children it is 25%.": "",
  "A black Labrador (BbEe) is crossed with a chocolate (brown) Labrador (bbEe). In Labrador coat color, B = black, b = brown, E = pigment deposited, e = no pigment (yellow). What fraction of the puppies are expected to be yellow?": "",
  "Focus on the E gene: Ee × Ee → 1 EE : 2 Ee : 1 ee. Only ee dogs are yellow (epistasis — ee masks the B gene). So 1/4 of puppies will be ee = yellow, regardless of their B genotype. The other 3/4 have at least one E and will show pigment (black or brown depending on B genotype).": "",
  "A person who is heterozygous for the sickle cell allele (HbA HbS) has both normal and sickle-shaped red blood cells. They generally do not show severe symptoms and have increased resistance to malaria. This heterozygote advantage, combined with the fact that one gene (HbS) causes effects in blood, spleen, kidneys, and lungs, demonstrates which TWO non-Mendelian patterns?": "",
  "Multiple alleles and sex-linked inheritance": "",
  "Epistasis and X-linked inheritance": "",
  "Codominance (both hemoglobin types expressed) and pleiotropy (one gene affects many organs)": "",
  "Incomplete dominance and polygenic inheritance": "",
  "The sickle cell trait demonstrates codominance at the molecular level — heterozygotes produce BOTH normal hemoglobin (HbA) and sickle hemoglobin (HbS), not an intermediate form. It also demonstrates pleiotropy because the single HbS gene mutation affects multiple organ systems (blood, spleen, kidneys, lungs, brain). The sickle cell gene is autosomal (chromosome 11), not X-linked.": "",
  "A color-blind man (X^c Y) marries a woman with normal vision whose father was color blind. What is the probability that their SON will be color blind?": "",
  "50%": "",
  "100%": "",
  "25%": "",
  "The woman's father was color blind (X^c Y), so he must have given her X^c. Since she has normal vision, her genotype must be X^C X^c (carrier). Crossed with a color-blind man (X^c Y): sons get their X from the mother — either X^C (normal) or X^c (color blind). So 50% of sons will be color blind. The father's X^c goes only to daughters, not sons (sons get Y from dad).": ""
}